Aim of Stack Using Linked List

To implement a stack data structure dynamically using a linked list, allowing push and pop operations without the size limitation of an array, and to demonstrate the Last In, First Out (LIFO) principle in a dynamic memory scenario.


PROGRAM:
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Node structure
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
};

// Top pointer
struct Node* top = NULL;

// Push operation: Insert element at top
void push(int value) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    if(newNode == NULL) {
        printf("Stack Overflow\n");
        return;
    }
    newNode->data = value;
    newNode->next = top; // Link new node to current top
    top = newNode;       // Update top
    printf("%d pushed to stack\n", value);
}

// Pop operation: Remove element from top
void pop() {
    if(top == NULL) {
        printf("Stack Underflow\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = top;
    top = top->next;     // Move top to next node
    printf("%d popped from stack\n", temp->data);
    free(temp);          // Free memory
}

// Peek operation: View top element
void peek()
